Advice - All Clear
 
 
Issued For: Deer Park
Incident Location: Foleys Rd, Deer Park
Incident Name:  
Issued: 02/02/16 2:39 PM
 
 
This is an All Clear message being issued by Metropolitan Fire Brigade for Deer Park.
 
The hazardous material leak at Sleepmaker  Foleys Rd, Deer Park is now safe.
 

People located within the area are now able to resume normal activities. 
 
This will be the final message for this incident. 
 
Safety Instructions:
  • If you are experiencing any symptoms that may be due to exposure, seek medical advice or call 'Nurse on Call' on 1300 606 024.

Advice
 
 
Issued For: Wye River, Separation Creek
Fire Origin: Wye River, Jamieson Creek
Incident Name: DELWP - WYE RIVER - JAMIESON TRACK - 1552223 
Issued: 02/02/16 5:25 PM


This Advice message is being issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning for Wye River, Separation Creek

The fire is now contained.

There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.

The Great Ocean Road is open and motorists are required to adhere to all traffic signs in the area. People should not be complacent and remain vigilant whilst there is fire activity in the area

Fire fighting resources will remain in place to extinguish any hot spots and to secure the fire perimeter.

Resident's and property owners who want to book or confirm an escorted visit into the Wye River and Separation Creek area please contact the Colac Otway Shire on 03 5232 9400.  Escort arrangements can change with minimal notice based on weather and safety considerations.
 
For all information about fires, storms and flooding preparedness, warnings and recovery please visit the Emergency Victoria website www.emergency.vic.gov.au

Road closures and no entry signs around the fire effected areas remain in place. Walking tracks leading into fire effected areas have also been closed. NO public access to these areas is permitted, with road closures reviewed daily and may be in place for some time. These areas include:
  • Jamieson Track, Separation Creek
  • Sarsfield Street, Separation Creek
  • Stanway Drive, Separation Creek
  • Olive Street, Separation Creek
  • The Boulevarde, Wye River
  • Bird Track, Wye River
  • Wallace Avenue, Wye River 

Wildlife response arrangements

The Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning (DELWP) has ongoing measures in place to enable the rescue, treatmentand rehabilitation of wildlife affected by fire.

To report injured wildlife outside the fire ground area contact Wildlife Victoria on 1300 094 535 or help for Wildlife on 0417 380 687

To report injured wildlife inside the fireground north of Kennett River and south of Cumberland River contact DELWP on 5233 5565

The fire ground remains closed to all unauthorised public

 
The next update is expected by 05/02/16 2:30 PM or as the situation changes.
 
Safety Information:
  • Review your bushfire survival plan.
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
  • If you have time check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions.
  • If you are experiencing smoke exposure, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.

Smoke Information:

  • The EPA currently has no reports of effected air quality in and around the Wye River and Separation Creek areas. Please refer to the EPA website for further information.
  • Smoke can affect people's health.
  • People with heart or lung conditions (including asthma), children, pregnant woman and older people are more sensitive to the effects of breathing smoke.
  • People with existing heart or lung conditions (including asthma) should follow the treatment plan advised by their doctor.
  • If you are experiencing any symptoms that may be due to smoke exposure, seek medical advice or call NURSE-ON-CALL on 1300 60 60 24.
  • Anyone experiencing wheezing, chest tightness and difficulty breathing should call 000.

 Stay Informed:

  • Community Recovery Information centre is located at the Colac Otway Shire Office, 69 Nelson Street, Apollo Bay. Open 10am - 4pm daily.
  • Contact the Colac Otway Shire Bushfire Information Call Centre on 03 5232 9400 and select option 1. Open 8:30am - 5pm weekdays.  Weekend arrangements to be confirm Friday 5 February 2016
  • Emergency Victoria [all incidents]  www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • Tune to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Call the Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667.
  • Deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the FireReady App or follow Vic Emergency on Twitter (#VicFires) or Facebook.
  • Road closures: check VicRoads website.
  • Environment Protection Authority www.epa.vic.gov.au

TEST Tsunami warning for Victoria.
        An undersea earthquake of magnitude 6.8 has occurred at  6:33 AM AWST on Monday 17 November 2014  centred OFF E. COAST OF N. ISLAND, N.Z..
        A threat of major land inundation, dangerous waves and strong ocean currents exists for the following areas:
- All low-lying coastal areas  from Lakes Entrance to SA Border
Dangerous inundation is expected in this zone after 4:00 pm (AWST) Monday
The Land Inundation Threat Zone includes West Coast, Central Coast, Central Gippsland Coast, East Gippsland Coast, Port Phillip, Western Port and Gippsland Lakes.
        A threat of dangerous waves, strong ocean currents and the possibility of
        inundation of the immediate foreshore exists for the following areas:
        - All coastal areas from West Coast, Central Coast, Central Gippsland Coast, East Gippsland Coast, Port Phillip, Western Port and Gippsland Lakes
        after 4:00 pm (AWST) Monday
        Caution, the first wave may not necessarily be the largest wave and
        tsunami waves are more dangerous and powerful than normal beach waves.
